{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"28b439d1-fb2e-4940-8748-121fcff935b7","content":"When `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is set to `1` (via `<startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">` in app config), it changes how the CLR activates legacy COM components and mixed-mode assemblies:\n\n**What it does:**\n- Binds CLR v2 (.NET 2.0/3.5) COM activation requests to the **current runtime** (e.g., CLR v4) instead of loading CLR v2 side-by-side.\n- Essentially tells CLR v4 to handle components that would normally require CLR v2.\n\n**Effect on runtime selection:**\n- Without it, a managed COM component built against .NET 2.0 triggers CLR v2 to load in-process (side-by-side).\n- With it, CLR v4 \"claims\" those activations, avoiding loading two runtimes in the same process.\n\n**Common use case:** Hosting .NET 2.0-era mixed-mode C++/CLI assemblies or COM objects in a .NET 4+ process without side-by-side CLR loading.\n\n**Caveat:** It can mask compatibility issues — the v2-targeted code runs on v4 without explicit retargeting, so subtle behavioral differences may go unnoticed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c06ed610-a945-4f70-a8f9-57c1f8c48503","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation log message related to `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy`. This is a .NET Framework question about runtime activation behavior. Let me answer from my knowledge since this is a well-known .NET configuration topic.","outputTokens":381,"requestId":"75C2:3766FA:D65629:FB457B:69FE8E18"},"id":"023ae87b-b796-4b3a-b475-49e7d47f25ee","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:30:10.975Z","parentId":"3054922d-4191-4582-862a-df7298c23682"}
